JD - 37 : 

Mechanical And Electrical Subsystem Assembly
- Perform installation of structural frames, brackets, antenna mounts, and internal trays using GD&T-verified drawings and mechanical BOMs.
- Route harnesses and connectors inside UAV fuselage sections based on wiring schematics and harness drawings; confirm connector mating by ID code and pin alignment.
- Support integration of Power Distribution Boards (PDBs) by verifying connector orientation, signal path routing, and secure mounting as per schematic references.
- Apply torque using calibrated tools according to defined torque specs (N¬∑m/in-lb), record values on checklist where required, and ensure visual confirmation (torque seal, color marking).

Component Fit-Up & Compatibility Troubleshooting
 - Verify part fitment and surface alignment using physical mock-ups, coordinate measuring arms, or laser alignment jigs.
 - Identify mismatched connector gender, harness length deviations, or mounting hole misalignments, and raise Non-Conformance Report (NCR) for resolution.
 - Recommend alternate routing paths for non-critical harnesses when original path causes interference, with approval from integration engineer.

Interpretation Of Engineering Drawings And Wiring Schematics
 - Independently read mechanical drawings with GD&T annotations, identify tolerancing zones, critical mounting hole locations, and symmetry references.
 - Interpret wiring schematics including signal paths, ground loops, and shielded line routing; understand polarity marking and connector cross-referencing.
 - Annotate drawings to mark deviations or undocumented design changes encountered during assembly, and route these notes for review.

Kitting Validation And Inventory Feedback
 - Validate BoM completeness against issued kits and flag shortages, overages, or alternate part substitutions using batch tags and ERP references.
 - Maintain segregation of kits by serial numbers and project codes to avoid cross-contamination; support traceability by tagging unused items before return to stores.
 - Report recurring kitting issues (e.g., missing hardware pack, wrong crimp connector variants) and suggest improvements to the kitting workflow.

Tool Calibration Compliance And Handling
 - Ensure torque tools, calipers, crimpers, and thermal guns are used only if within calibration window; sign daily pre-use checklist.
 - Log tool usage in traceability sheets and coordinate tool return for recalibration based on expiration tags or usage cycle flags.
 - Identify damaged tools (bent torque drivers, cracked handles, faulty gauges) and initiate tool quarantine request with metrology/QA.

Technical Documentation And Assembly Traceability
 - Complete routing checklists, electrical continuity check logs, torque application sheets, and batch build reports based on platform configuration.
 - Document any observed fitment issues or undocumented wire color variations in the build log and flag these to QA or Design Engineer.
 - File completed job sheets into project folders with correct part number, drawing revision, and build serial tagging.

PLM System Usage And Revision Tracking
 - Access Teamcenter/Windchill to retrieve latest drawing revisions, change notes, and related documentation for assigned assemblies.
 - Cross-check drawing revision number and configuration ID with build instructions; request clarification for ECRs in process or drawings under review.
 - Support Engineering Change Request (ECR) logging by capturing part-level impact details during deviation or assembly interruptions.

Calibration Log Tracking And Process Support
 - Maintain daily calibration board in assigned area, highlighting upcoming expirations and tools under recertification hold.
 - Support audit teams during calibration record reviews by retrieving usage logs, calibration certificates, and tool tag photos.
 - Identify repetitive calibration misses or booking delays and recommend improved tracking measures (e.g., barcode-based flagging or digital alerts).

Process Compliance, Safety & Quality Coordination: Follow cleanroom-level ESD protocols:
 - wrist strap validation, conductive mats, safe cable dressing, and connector sealing practices.
 - Perform Foreign Object Debris (FOD) inspections post-integration and before QA handover using flashlights, air blowers, and magnet wands.
 - Interface with QA inspectors during in-process quality checks, torque witnessing, or functional test readiness assessments.

Continuous Learning And Integration Optimization
 - Maintain a structured log of builds executed, tools used, part variants handled, and errors encountered for performance tracking.
 - Attend knowledge sessions led by Engineers on connector families, torque theory, updated harness trees, or platform-specific quirks.
 - Propose improvements to assembly fixture layout, part access during integration, or tool routing to improve ergonomics and reduce cycle time.

